What could be wrong?

I analyzed loss_mmod_::compute_loss_value_and_gradient() and compared it with the original document https://arxiv.org/pdf/1502.00046.pdf. I found several potential bugs I would like to discuss.
**---- #1 ----**
In the document describing the algorithm to perform MMOD object detection on page 5, in the pseudo code of the algorithm on line 5 there is: 
_if D i does not overlap {D i−1 ,D i−2 ,...} then_
In c++ implementation there is:
               _for (unsigned long i = 0; i < dets.size() && final_dets.size() < max_num_dets; ++i)
                {
                    if (overlaps_any_box_nms(final_dets, dets[i].rect))
                        continue;
                    const std::pair<double,unsigned int> hittruth = find_best_match(*truth, dets[i].rect);
                    final_dets.push_back(dets[i].rect);_

Let's consider this case: set of detections contains 3 detections in following configuration: D1 overlaps D2, D2 overlaps D3 but D3 does not overlap D1.
Difference: **pseudocode algorithm would process only D1, C++ implementation would process D1 and D3.**

**---- #2 ----**
In c++ code there is a loop over all input samples (images): 
            _const float* out_data = output_tensor.host();
            for (long i = 0; i < output_tensor.num_samples(); ++i)
            {
                tensor_to_dets(input_tensor, output_tensor, i, dets, -options.loss_per_false_alarm, sub);
                .....
                for (auto&& x : *truth)
                {
                    if (!x.ignore)
                    {
                        point p = image_rect_to_feat_coord(input_tensor, x, sub);
                        loss -= out_data[p.y()*output_tensor.nc() + p.x()];_
  
While method **tensor_to_dets** takes into account index i of the processed image and adjusts pointer to raw data like this: _const float* out_data = output_tensor.host() + output_tensor.nr()*output_tensor.nc()*i;_
it is forgotten in the loss calculation here:  _loss -= out_data[p.y()*output_tensor.nc() + p.x()];_
The same problem occurs at the end of the cycle:
               _for (auto&& x : final_dets)
                {
                    loss += out_data[x.tensor_offset];_
Here _tensor_offset_ again does not contain the image index adjustment. 
**In both cases output data of the 1st image is used in the particular calculation for all of the images.

**---- #3 ----**
Intersection over union is implemented strangely in c++. Here is the code:
   _inline double box_intersection_over_union (
        const drectangle& a,
        const drectangle& b
    ) 
    {
        const double inner = a.intersect(b).area();
        if (inner == 0)
            return 0;
        **const double outer = (a+b).area();**
        return inner/outer;
    }_

Outer area is calculated for the rectangle calculated from a+b operation. This operation returns rectangle bounding both input rectangles. Area of bounding rectangle can be significantly larger than area of an union of rectangles. Correct implementation should be:
outer = a.area()+b.area()-inner;

